\begin_layout Itemize
Remember the wage regression equation (true model) 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  \begin{aligned}
  \log W_{i}  &=&  & \beta_{0}+\beta_{1}S_{i}+\beta_{2}A_{i}+u_{i} \\
  E[u_{i}|S_{i},A_{i}]    &=& & 0
  \end{aligned}
  \]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \(W_{i}\)
\end_inset

 is wage, 
\begin_inset Formula \(S_{i}\)
\end_inset

 is the years of schooling, and 
\begin_inset Formula \(A_{i}\)
\end_inset

 is the ability. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose that you omit 
\begin_inset Formula \(A_i\)
\end_inset

 and run the following regression instead. 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  \log W_{i}  =   \alpha_{0}+\alpha_{1} S_{i} + v_i 
  \]
\end_inset

Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula \(v_i = \beta_2 A_i + u_i\)
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \(S_i\)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \(v_i\)
\end_inset

 is likely to be correlated. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You might want to add more and more additional variables to capture the effect of ability.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Test scores, GPA, SAT scores, etc\SpecialChar ldots
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
However, can you make sure that 
\begin_inset Formula \(S_i\)
\end_inset

 is indeed exogenous after adding many control variables? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multivariate regression cannot deal with the presence of 
\series bold
unobserved heterogeneity
\series default
 that matters both in wage and years of schooling. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
