\begin_layout Itemize
Let's start with a simple case. 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \epsilon_i, 
  \]
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \(Cov(x_i, \epsilon_i) \neq 0\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now, we consider another variable 
\begin_inset Formula \(z_i\)
\end_inset

, which we call 
\series bold
instrumental variable (IV)
\series default
. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instrumental variable 
\begin_inset Formula \(z_i\)
\end_inset

 should satisfies the following two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Independence
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula \(Cov(z_i, \epsilon_i) = 0\)
\end_inset

. No correlation between IV and error. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Relevance
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula \(Cov(z_i, x_i) \neq 0\)
\end_inset

. There should be correlation between IV and endogenous variable 
\begin_inset Formula \(x_i\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Idea: Use the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula \(x_i\)
\end_inset

 
\series bold
induced by instrument 
\begin_inset Formula \(z_i\)
\end_inset


\series default
 to estimate the direct (causal) effect of 
\begin_inset Formula \(x_i\)
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula \(y_i\)
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta_1\)
\end_inset

!. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
