\begin_layout Enumerate
Intuitively, the OLS estimator captures the correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula \(x\)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \(y\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If there is no correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula \(x\)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \(\epsilon\)
\end_inset

, it captures the causal effect 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta_1\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If not, the OLS estimator captures both direct and indirect effect, the latter of which is bias. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, let's capture the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula \(x\)
\end_inset

 due to instrument 
\begin_inset Formula \(z\)
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Such a variation should exist under 
\series bold
relevance
\series default
 assumption. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Such a variation should not be correlated with the error under 
\series bold
independence assumption
\series default
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
By looking at the correlation between such variation and 
\begin_inset Formula \(y\)
\end_inset

, you can get the causal effect 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta_1\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
