\begin_layout Itemize
Why does this work? Let's go back to the simple example with 1 endogenous variable and 1 IV. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the first stage, we estimate
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  x_i = \pi_0 + \pi_1 z_i + v_i
  \]
\end_inset

by OLS and obtain the fitted value 
\begin_inset Formula \(\widehat{x}_i = \widehat{\pi}_0 + \widehat{\pi}_1 z_i\)
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the second stage, we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \widehat{x}_i + u_i
  \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula \(\widehat{x}_i\)
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula \(z_i\)
\end_inset

, which is uncorrelated with 
\begin_inset Formula \(u_i\)
\end_inset

, the second stage can estimate 
\begin_inset Formula \(\beta_1\)
\end_inset

 without bias. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can you see the importance of both independence and relevance asssumption here? (More formal discussion later) 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
