\begin_layout Itemize
In the simple example above, The first stage is
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  x_i = \pi_0 + \pi_1 z_i + v_i
  \]
\end_inset

and the second stage is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \widehat{x}_i + u_i
  \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The second stage would have perfect multicollinarity if 
\begin_inset Formula \(\pi_1 = 0\)
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula \(\widehat{x}_i = \pi_0\)
\end_inset

). 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Back to the general case, the first stage for 
\begin_inset Formula \(X_k\)
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
  X_{ki} = \pi_0 + \pi_1 Z_{1i} + \cdots + \pi_M Z_{Mi} + \pi_{M+1} W_{1i} + \cdots + \pi_{M+R} W_{Ri}
  \]
\end_inset

and one of 
\begin_inset Formula \(\pi_1 , \cdots, \pi_M\)
\end_inset

 should be non-zero. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intuitively speaking, 
\series bold
the instruments should be correlated with endogenous variables after controlling for exogenous variables
\series default
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
